Currently, it we have a complex JSON response from a web request action, we can only do a simple traversing of it using JSON object notation. However, should there be arrays in the response and we need to get a certain array key, that notation wouldn't work unless we use an array index, which is not ideal.

For example, if we want to query Insight object attributes, we can send a request to {{/jira/rest/insight/1.0/object/33542/attributes}} and then if we need to get this value from the response:
{noformat}
webhookResponse.body.objectEntries.[0].attributes[?(@.objectTypeAttributeId==3701)].objectAttributeValues[0].user.key{noformat}
It is not possible to do that like that. Best we could do is to hard code an array index in smart values:
{noformat}
webhookResponse.body.objectAttributeValues.get(4).user.key{noformat}
But this is far less than ideal.

A4J should support for flexible querying of the JSON data, such as:
 - possibility to run JSONPath expressions directly on the webhook response
 - possibility to add expressions like "objectTypeAttributeId = xxx" in the smart value syntax.

h3. Issue

Automation rules using the *Incoming Webhook* trigger fail to run if the JSON payload provided by the webhook contains the *data* tag with just a string in it:
{code}
{
  "data": "Julien"
}
{code}

h3. Notes

Note that the Payload received by the Automation rule is properly parsed if the *data* tag contains a map of data. In such case, the rule is properly triggered:
{code}
{
    "data": {
        "name": "Julien"
    }
}
{code}

Another note is that the same issue will happen if the payload contains the tag *issues*, as it is also a tag which is processed in a special way by Automation for Jira.

h3. Steps to replicate:

# Configure an automation rule using:
-- the *When: Incoming webhook* trigger
-- the log action used to record the payload coming from the webhook, via the smart value webhookData
 !Step1.png|thumbnail! 
# Take note of the *Webhook URL* from that rule
# Open an app that can be used to send a POST request to the A4J rule webhook URL. For example, I'm using Postman
# Send a POST request to the webhook URL using:
#- The webhook URL in the URL field
#- the POST method
#- the "content-type" header set to "application/json"
#- the following payload:
{code}
{
  "data": "Julien"
}
{code}

h3. Expected results

- A4J should come back to the client that sent the webhook with the 200 HTTP code:
 !Step3.png|thumbnail! 
- The incoming webhook should be processed by the rule and the execution show be with the "SUCCESS" status in the audit log:
 !Step4.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Actual results

A4J returns a 400 HTTP error with the following message:
{code}
{
    "warningMessages": [],
    "errorMessages": [
        "Can not instantiate value of type [map type; class java.util.LinkedHashMap, [simple type, class java.lang.String] -> [simple type, class java.lang.Object]] from JSON String; no single-String constructor/factory method (through reference chain: com.codebarrel.automation.api.webhook.IncomingWebhook[\"data\"])"
    ],
    "errors": {},
    "status": 400
}
{code}
 !Step2.png|thumbnail! 


h3. Workaround

There is unfortunately no easy workaround. This bug comes from the fact that, by design, the Automation source code expects the *data* tag to come with the format below, and fails if *data* only comes as a string:
{code}
data: {
key: value,
key2: value,
...
}
{code}

The only way to work around this bug is to modify the format of the webhook payload which is sent to the Automation rule. This might or might not be possible, if this webhook is sent by using a 3rd party application.

Description

Workaround from https://docs.automationforjira.com/issues/edit-additional-fields.html#field-syntax-examples:

{code}
{
    "fields": {
  "First Field" : { "value": "First value", "child": { "value" : "Child value"} }
    }
}
{code}

(i) This was cloned from https://codebarrel.atlassian.net/browse/AUT-327

Right now it's possible to have rules interact with each other through webhooks, including passing smart values on the sending payload, so that the rule that checks for incoming webhooks can use that.

However, it's not clear what the correct syntax to use these values is and which data can be handled this way. For example, the Version Name smart value is the following:

{noformat}
version.name
{noformat}

But the following needs to be configured on the webhook body for the incoming webhook rule to be able to use that smart value:

{noformat}
{"whVersion":"{{version.name}}"}
{noformat}

Having a page listing these interactions and values could massively improve the user experience when using such interactions.

h3. Issue Summary
In the Automation for Jira rule to copy the entry of 'wrok log' from parent issue to 'linked' issue, Work Log entries from 'parent' ticket do not get copied to 'linked' ticket after 20 entries.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a simple A4J rule to copy Work Log entries from 'parent' ticket to 'linked' ticket.
 !A4J rule.png|thumbnail! 
# We are using below code snippet to copy the 'work log' values from 'parent' to 'linked' ticket.
{code}
{
  "update": {
    "worklog" : [
      {
        "add": {
          "timeSpent" : "{{#debug}}{{triggerissue.worklog.timeSpent.last}}{{/}}"
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
{code}
# Create 2 tickets and link them (relates or any other). Start entering 'work log' values on them. Please check the 'linked' ticket to make sure values are getting copied through A4J rule. 
# Enter 20 values. All 20 entries will be copied from 'parent' to 'linked' issues as expected. However, from the 21st entry, for all the subsequent entries, the new values entered in 'parent' ticket will not be copied to 'linked' issue. 'Linked' issue just copies the 20th value every time to the 'linked' issue and vice-versa.

h3. Expected Results
Correct values from 'parent' issue must be copied to 'linked' issue everytime.

h3. Actual Results
After 20 'work log' entries, for all subsequent entries, the 20th entry will be copied from the 'parent' issue to the 'linked' issue.

Screenshots of 'parent' ticket work log entries:
 !Parent Ticket_main page.png|thumbnail!  !Parent ticket_workLog_part_1.png|thumbnail!  !Parent ticket_workLog_part_2.png|thumbnail! 
(i) Notice, after 20 entries, next entries are 21, 22, 23 & 24 minutes.
Screenshots of 'linked' ticket work log entries:
 !Linked Ticket_main page.png|thumbnail!  !Linked ticket_workLog_part_1.png|thumbnail! !Linked ticket_workLog_part_2.png|thumbnail! !Linked ticket_workLog_part_3.png|thumbnail! 
(i) Notice, after 20 entries, the subsequent entries are still for 20 minutes.
h3. Workaround
 Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available.

h3. Problem Definition

When comparing the issue field *Request Type*, the initial results in the dropdown show the last 50 *Request Types* updated, but when you start to type to execute a search, the results don't bring *hidden Request Types*.
h3. Suggested Solution

Show *Hidden Request Types* in search results.
h3. Why this is important

When the user has more than 50 *Request Types*, it is impossible to use the Issue fields conditions since there is a chance of the *hidden Request Types* won't appear in the initial results. The only solution is to use the workarounds below, which may be more complex for some users than others, depending on their actual scenario.
h3. Workaround
 # Use the *JQL condition* querying the *Request Type*:
{noformat}
"Request Type" in ("Request Type Name"){noformat}

 # Use the *Advanced compare condition*, using the first value as
{noformat}
{{issue.Request Type.requestType.name}}{noformat}

Currently, we can list comments by adding this smart value:

{{#issue.comments}}
Comment by: {{author.displayName}} at: {{created}}
{{body}}
{{/}}

But if we try to use any kind of conditions inside of smart values, they doesn't apply.

{{#issue.comments}}
{{#if(true)}}
{{body}}
{{/}}
{{/}}

{{#issue.comments}}
{{#if(author.displayName.endsWith("Automation"))}}
{{body}}
{{/}}
{{/}}

{{#issue.comments}}
{{#if(not(author.displayName.endsWith("Automation")))}}
