And we have similar feature for JIRA Cloud that would be good if we had on JIRA Server/DC too.

Automation for Jira's IF / ELSE condition doesn't quite behave as many programmers expect, and the documentation doesn't make a note on it.
h3. Situation
{panel}
We have two issues:
 * KEY-123
 * KEY-456
 And 3 JQL/conditions:
 * Condition A is matched by KEY-123 and KEY-456
 * Condition B is matched by KEY-123{panel}
h3. Rule
{panel}
Scheduled execution:
{code:java}
When condition A is met:
-- If condition B is met: add label B
-- Else, add label C
{code}
{panel}
h3. Expected behavior
{panel}
To many programmers, the expected behavior would be:
 * KEY-123 gets labeled as B
 * KEY-456 gets labeled as C{panel}
h3. Actual behavior
{panel}
Only KEY-123 gets labeled as B and KEY-456 isn't edited at all.
 On a *next execution*, if no issues are met by condition B, then KEY-456 gets labelled as C.
{panel}
h3. Suggestion

The note that's missing on the IF/ELSE documentation (for both [Cloud|https://support.atlassian.com/jira-software-cloud/docs/automation-conditions/] and [Server/DC|https://confluence.atlassian.com/automation/conditions-993924794.html]) is something like:
{panel:bgColor=#deebff}
(on) Note: The path of IF/ELSE conditions aren't executed for _each issue individually_, but for any match in the rule's trigger condition.

If the rule's trigger brings 20 issues and a IF matches 2 and ELSE, 18, the rule won't perform the actions of the IF block for the 2 issues and ELSE's block for 18, but only the IF's for the 2 issues.

The ELSE block only gets executed if _none_ of the issues matches the IF condition.
{panel}

h3. Issue Summary

The table AO_589059_RULE_STAT_ROLLUP_DAY contains information on Automation for Jira Rules’(A4J) run for statistics and audit log. Every time an action is performed against an Automation for Jira Rule, an entry is added to this table, data older than 35 days is removed from this table by an A4J internal job, however the ID just keeps on incrementing. 

Not all DBMSs are able to automatically revert the ID back to starting point, this generates warnings and could lead to impact on A4J functionality as the data type limit is reached, at this point this issue was already identified in MSSQL, MySQL and ORACLE. 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
Have table AO_589059_RULE_STAT_ROLLUP_DAY ID column reach maximum value (2147483647) of the data type

h3. Expected Results
ID reset back to initial value, normal Automation execution

h3. Actual Results
ID gets stuck at maximum value, automation starts reporting issues and failing. The below exception is thrown in the atlassian-jira.log file:
{noformat}
System Error message :
com.codebarrel.jira.plugin.automation.schedule.RuleInsightsUpdateScheduler.DAY.scheduler MessageQueryException: Caught BatchUpdateException for insert into `AO_589059_RULE_STAT_ROLLUP_DAY` (`CATEGORY`, `CLIENT_KEY`, `CREATED`, `DURATION`, `END_TO_END_DURATION`, `EXECUTION_COUNT`, `QUEUED_ITEM_COUNT`, `RULE_ID`) values (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?) BatchU
{noformat}

h3. Workaround

The following SQL queries seek to revert the ID back to initial value, allowing A4J to continue working as expected. As there are 35 days worth of data is unlikely that the ID will reach maximum value before the table is automatically purged.

# Stop all Jira nodes.
# Backup the database.
# Run one of SQL queries below, depending on your DBMS type
# Start Jira.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
(!) *PLEASE READ*: As with all recommendations made by Atlassian Support, please follow best practices for Change Management and make sure to *test and validate* these steps in a lower environment (staging, development, testing, etc) *prior to* rolling any changes into a Production environment. This is to validate these changes and ensure that they will function will within your infrastructure prior to placing these changes in production.
{panel}

*MSSQL*
{code:sql}
DBCC CHECKIDENT ('<SCHEMA>.AO_589059_RULE_STAT_ROLLUP_DAY', RESEED, 0);
{code}
Update <SCHEMA> to match Jira's schema

*MySQL*
{code:java}
ALTER TABLE AO_589059_RULE_STAT_ROLLUP_DAY AUTO_INCREMENT = 1;
{code}

According to - [https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/alter-table.html] under section *To reset the current auto-increment value*, you cannot reset the counter to a value less than or equal to the value that is currently in use. For both InnoDB and MyISAM, if the value is less than or equal to the maximum value currently in the AUTO_INCREMENT column, the value is reset to the current maximum AUTO_INCREMENT column value plus one.

This may mean we may have to purge all the records in the table (meaning you won't have statistics for 1d report).

h3. Issue Summary

Upon attempting to utilize the "update" function (rather than "fields") in the advanced field configuring, A4J will incorrectly refuse a valid JSON format as if the 'add', 'set', and 'edit' functions were not present.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a new rule in A4J using any trigger
 # Add an *Edit issue* action and expand the "Advanced Configuration" settings.
 # Input the same JSON featured on the [Advanced field editing|https://confluence.atlassian.com/automation/advanced-field-editing-993924663.html] article.
{code:java}
{
    "update": {
        "description": {
            "set": "a new description"
        },
        "labels": [{
                "add": "test-label"
        }]
    },
    "fields": {
        "summary": "woohoo! a new summary"
    }
}
{code}
 # Upon saving the rule, A4J will provide the following error message on the UI:
{quote}(!) Additional fields contains invalid 'update' operations for field 'description'. You can use 'add', 'remove', 'set' or 'edit' for operations.
{quote}

(i) If you remove the quotes around 'set' and 'add', A4J will accept the JSON as valid, however, the rule will fail during the execution with the following error:
{quote}(!) *Some errors:*
 Action details:
 Edit issue
 Error while parsing additional fields. Not valid JSON.
{quote}
h3. Expected Results

A4J successfully accepts the JSON format informed on our official documentation.
h3. Actual Results

Valid JSON's are not accepted by the tool, while invalid ones are.
h3. Workaround

Avoid the usage of the *Advanced Field Editing* feature along with 'update'.
 Currently, there is no known workaround for the use of the update function. A workaround will be added here when available

When a JSM ticket is closed, we would like to include details from a linked issue from another project into the customer email, but only for a specific link type. The second project is a Jira Software project. 

Steps to reproduce:
* Customer creates a JSM ticket
* The ticket is linked to multiple Jira Software issues. One of the links is the link type "X"
* Close JSM ticket
* Email should be sent from JSM ticket and include details about the linked Jira Software issue if the link type is "X", like:
{quote}
Linked issue: {{issue.issuelinks.outwardIssue}} 
Summary: {{issue.issuelinks.outwardIssue.fields.summary}} 
Description: {{issue.issuelinks.outwardIssue.fields.description}}
{quote}
